  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key examples include:\n\n1. United States: Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and USA PATRIOT Act\n2. European Union: Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n3. United Kingdom: Proceeds of Crime Act\n4. International standards set by the Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n\nThese regulations typically require financial institutions to:\n- Perform customer due diligence\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement internal control systems\n- Conduct ongoing monitoring of financial activities\n\nThe goal is to detect and prevent money laundering, terrorist financing, and other financial crimes.",
